Explore WES VQSR VCF

Alexey Larionov

15/03/2019

started: AL13Aug2018
last updated: AL15Mar2019

Summary

Read vcf to R (4,451 variants x 710 cases) and explore selected QC metrics

Exploration shows that: before and after applying filters WES-NFE dataset has much less num of vars than ampliseq data:

  • ~4.5k vs ~13k before filtering
  • ~3.5k vs ~7k after filtering

In both WES and Ampliseq, missingness of genotypes is higher in NFE than in WECARE.

Explored hard filters at this stage:

  • Average DP > 10x num samples
  • VQSR PASS
  • QUAL > 150 (small additional efect)

Explore missed values in standard VEP fileds

# Count missed values
sum(is.na(fixed.df))
## [1] 22416
sum(fixed.df == "", na.rm=T)
## [1] 0
sum(fixed.df == ".", na.rm=T)
## [1] 0
# Function to check for blanks in a vector
sum_na.udf <- function(x){sum(is.na(x))}

# Look up columns that contain blanks
x <- apply(fixed.df,2,sum_na.udf)
names(x) <- colnames(fixed.df)
x[x>0]
##              ID    BaseQRankSum ClippingRankSum             END  HaplotypeScore       MQRankSum  ReadPosRankSum          VQSLOD         culprit 
##            4451              40              40            4451            4451              40              41            4451            4451
# A uniform field (Were any of the samples downsampled?)
table(fixed.df$DS)
## 
## FALSE 
##  4451
# Remove empty and uniform fields
fixed.df <- fixed.df %>% 
  select(-ID, -END, -HaplotypeScore, -VQSLOD, -culprit, -DS)

# Clean-up
rm(x, sum_na.udf)
